title: For Sale/Trade:  Firearms Trust Planning for large collections or NFA items.
postcontent:
http://www.rocketcitylawyers.com/practice/firearms-trust-planning/

I am an attorney in Huntsville that serves clients throughout the state with firearms trust planning services for those with large collections, NFA items, or concerns about handing down their collections to their family.



What is a Gun Trust?

Firearms Trusts were developed to make the purchase, ownership, and inheritance of firearms covered by the National Firearms Act (“NFA”) easier. The NFA regulates “Title II” weapons and include machine guns, short-barreled rifles and shotguns, suppressors, destructive devices, and Any Other Weapons (AOWs).

Title II weapons can be acquired individually or through an entity such as trust. Individuals must submit fingerprints, a photograph, pay for the $200 tax stamp, and obtain permission from the Chief Law Enforcement Officer (CLEO) in the jurisdiction in which they reside. In some jurisdictions the sheriff will refuse to sign off on any such purchases as a matter of policy. Such blanket policies prevent law-abding citizens from being able to obtain these weapons at all. Once approved, only the approved individual may hold or use the weapons. Violations can result in 10-year prison sentence and a $250,000 fine.

By creating a firearms trust, some of these barriers to ownership can be surmounted. Trusts may legally own such firearms, and bypass requirements for a photograph, fingerprints, and the requirement that a CLEO approve the purchase of the regulated firearm or device. It also allows for multiple individuals to utilize the firearm.

Beyond acquisition, a Firearms Trust may have additional benefits- it is designed for the sole purpose of acquiring, holding, and eventually distributing regulated and regulated weapons, ammunition, and accessories. Firearms trusts also help owners of weapons and devices regulated under the NFA from subjecting their family to “accidental felonies” upon their death. Although the owner may be registered to own such weapons, their family members or executors are not, and in most instances possession of these kinds of weapons without appropriate registration is a felony. a properly drafted Firearms trust will allow the beneficiaries o the trust to receive the weapons and other items without unintentionally committing a felony. Because items contained within a trust avoid probate, the contents of the trust and how and to whom they are distributed will remain totally private.

Not Just for NFA Weapons

All firearms owners should consider establishing a Firearms Trust to hold their weapons collection, even if they don’t own any regulated weapons. Recently, Congress has taken up legislation to ban a wide variety of semi-automatic firearms. Some legislators and pundits have made no secret of their wish to confiscate all firearms and accessories, and barring that, to prohibit the transfer of any “grandfathered” weapons and to require any such weapons to be surrender to the state at the current owner’s death.

Although the law of Firearms Trusts is still developing, it may be advisable to transfer non-regulated weapons into a trust prior to the enactment of any such legislation. This may avoid a scenario in which your family is forced to surrender your prized collection after you are gone. Proper planning can allow you to establish a legacy of responsible firearm ownership and use for generations to come.

An Important Part of a More Comprehensive Estate Plan

We offer three levels of Firearms Trust planning. The Bronze Edition is relatively inexpensive and is designed to hold only NFA regulated weapons. To keep cost to a minimum, it is provided without detailed consultation. The Silver Edition is the most popular option, and is designed for the firearms collector who understands the value of proper planning when dealing with NFA items (suppressors, etc.) as well as non-NFA items (regular rifles pistols and shotguns), and it will protect everyone that may come in contact with the collection and to avoid the likelihood of an “accidental felony”. The Gold Edition is crafted to assist clients with extensive collections, specific firearms issues, or advanced planning needs.

Often times, clients know they need to put proper planning in place but procrastinate in doing so. We want all of our clients to have comprehensive planning in place, which is why we offer a free Silver Edition Firearms Trust to our clients who engage us in other comprehensive trust-based planning. Contact us for more details about this offer!

title: For Sale:  Noreen -- Bad s 338 Lapua w/ Timney upgrade .338
postcontent:
Noreen has created the ONLY SEMI-AUTOMATIC .300 WIN MAG and .338 Lapua on the market. The BAD NEWS is a custom-made AR-style rifle that is chambered in the increasingly popular 338 Lapua as well as the powerful 300 WIN MAG. These cartridges give you much greater velocity and power than the typical .308, and as far as ballistics are concerned, the BAD NEWS rifle is going to be the flatter shooting gun for long range shots.

The BAD NEWS rifle is a piston-driven semi-auto; this means you can expect greater range and a higher level of reliability by running a cleaner and cooler rifle. The muzzle break on these Noreen’s significantly suppresses recoil. Additionally, the semi-auto nature of the rifle will naturally recoil less than a bolt action because part of the felt recoil is going to chamber the next round. Lighter recoil is a huge advantage when you’re looking for a rifle with a faster and more accurate follow-up shot.

This piston-driven system is unlike any other AR-10 on the market. The piston movement is strictly in the action, after the bullet has already left the barrel. This is a huge advantage on a precision rifle compared to conventional piston driven setups found in standard AR's. In those rifles, an LWRC REPR, POF P308, etc. the piston runs parallel to the barrel and moves while the bullet is still in the barrel creating unwanted barrel harmonics which adversely affect accuracy. This rifle's piston is located in the receiver and not along the barrel so the bullet is out of the barrel by the time the piston is working to chamber another round and keep your action cool and clean with no gas ever entering the action.

The semi-automatic will not only give you a much faster follow-up shot, it also allows you to stay focused on your target, optic and the trigger, instead of having to manually operate a bolt-action rifle; all subsequent rounds are chambered by the rifle itself during the gas or blowback operation of the action.

The weapon easily disassembles like the standard AR for quick and easy cleaning and reassembly. The piston system drastically reduces fouling, and no venting means no holes for dirt and other contaminants to enter the system.

The full-length Picatinny rail on the receiver will allow you to mount scopes, lights, lasers, bipods, bayonets, etc. The adjustable cheek rest stock option is an added upgrade free bonus.

The innovative Noreen Bad News .338 Lapua provides tactical marksmen with the performance of a powerful and proven long range cartridge with the numerous advantages of the venerable AR platform. The Noreen 338 Lapua weighs only 13 pounds, and it vastly outperforms comparable bolt-action sniper rifles. This rifle comes with a custom muzzle-break and semi-auto action that significantly suppresses recoil. In the AR tradition, the Bad News 338 Lapua disassembles quickly for easy cleaning, then reasembles with no loss of zero. The familiar fit and feel of a conventional AR rifle makes the transition to the more powerful sniper rifle seamless. This Noreen includes an ultra-heavy duty Plano case, which is far superior to a pelican style case. 100% Made in the USA.

Effective to 1500 yards

Receiver is machined from a billet of 6061 T6 aluminum

postcontent: Fully Engraved 1861 Colt Navy presentation Revolver 36 caliber, very early serial number 9765. I am selling this gun on consignment. It is out of an old Indian Trading Post from Gallup, New Mexico where it has been stored in a vault for over 25 years. This gun is in superb (museum quality) condition. The gun is silver plated and fully engraved by Gustave Young who was Colt's premier engraver from the 1850s through the 1870s. He is often referred to as the Picasso of engravers. His "signature" mark is the dog/wolf head show here in photo #24. The gun's grips are ivory and it has all matching serial numbers. This gun was obviously a custom order gun made as a presentation piece. The back of the back strap was left blank where a persons name would have been engraved
